Part 1: Introduction

1.1 Overview

MK-Ultra is a dual-nature programming language ecosystem consisting of two integrated languages:

Language Type Purpose
Maia Compiled systems language OS kernels, drivers, embedded systems, performance-critical code
Koda Interpreted scripting language Embedded scripting, standalone shell, build automation, web development

1.2 Design Principles

```toml
[design_principles]
safety_first = true
no_garbage_collection = true
zero_cost_abstractions = true
pascal_syntax = true
no_macros = true
toml_configuration = true
markdown_documentation = true
self_hosting = true
no_llvm = true
```

1.3 Language Relationship

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                           MK-Ultra                                       │
├─────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────┤
│            Maia                  │                Koda                   │
│    (Compiled Systems Lang)       │      (Interpreted Scripting Lang)     │
├─────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────┤
│ • No GC                         │ • Embedded (Lua-style)                 │
│ • Compile-time RC               │ • Standalone shell (Bash-style)        │
│ • Borrow checker                │ • Async/await                          │
│ • Reference capabilities        │ • Native templates                     │
│ • Explicit allocators           │ • Built-in VCS                         │
│ • Inline assembly               │ • Web framework (first-class)          │
│ • 4 backends (x86/ARM/RV/WASM)  │ • FFI via Maia                         │
│ • FFI to 7 languages            │ • Runs on Maia VM                      │
│ • Self-hosted                   │                                        │
└─────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────┘
```

